88–Deceased","1588–Male":"1588–Deceased","1590–1630":"1590–1630","1628–1736":"1628–1736","1572–Male":"1572–Deceased","1588":"1588","about 1625":"about 1625","1630":"1630","1572":"1572","about 1588":"about 1588","1628":"1628","1590":"1590","1736":"1736","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Evans","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: derivative of   Evan  , from <i>Efan</i>, <i>Ifan</i>, medieval forms of <i>Ieuan</i> (from Latin <i>Johannes</i>, the source of English <i>John</i>), dating from <i>c.</i> 1500, with the post-medieval patronymic suffix <i>-s</i>. Welsh <i>Sion</i> was a separate borrowing of English <i>John</i>, and <i>Evan</i> (<i>Ieuan</i>) and <i>Sion</i> developed as independent names."],"variants":[{"name":"Evanson","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Chesire): patronymic meaning ‘son of <i>Evan</i>’. See   Evans  .","Americanized form of Norwegian   Evensen   and of the much less common Swedish cognate <b>Evensson</b>. Compare   Eavenson   2 and   Evenson   1.","Probably also an Americanized form of Swedish <b>Ivansson</b>: patronymic from the personal name   Ivan  , of Slavic (Russian) origin."]},{"name":"Ivans","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Oxfordshire): variant of   Evans  .","In some cases also an Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Ivanc</b> and also of some other Slavic patronymics from the personal name   Ivan  ."]},{"name":"Ivens","meanings":["English (Warwickshire): variant of   Evans  .","Flemish, Dutch, and North German: patronymic from the shortened ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ive</i>, <i>Ivo</i>, from Middle High German <i>îwe</i> ‘(bow of) yew’."]},{"name":"Avans","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Welsh   Evans  ."]},{"name":"Evens","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Evans  .","German: variant of   Ewens  ."]},{"name":"Ivins","meanings":["English: variant of   Evans  ."]},{"name":"Evins","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Evans  ."]},{"name":"Evan","meanings":["Welsh (southern): from the personal name <i>Evan</i>, itself from <i>Ieuan</i>, a Welsh derivative of Latin <i>Johannes</i> (English <i>John</i>). See   Evans  ."]}]},{"name":"Hiram","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by a king of Tyre who is repeatedly mentioned in the Bible (2 Samuel 2:11; 1 Kings 5; 9:11; 10:11; 1 Chronicles 14:1; 2 Chronicles 2:11) as supplying wood, craftsmen, and money to enable David and Solomon to construct various buildings. It was also the name of a craftsman of Tyre who worked in brass for Solomon (1 Kings 7:13). The name is presumably of Semitic origin, but is probably a Phoenician name; if it is Hebrew, it may be a shortened form of <i>Ahiram</i> ‘brother of the exalted’. In England, the name was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, but soon dropped out of regular use. It is still used occasionally in the United States."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Hiram Evans was born about 1588, in Aberdeenshire, Scotland as the son of James Evans. He married Sarah Jane Robinson about 1625, in Aberdeenshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland."},"et":{"about 1588–":"umbes 1588–Surnud","1588–Male":"1588–Surnud","1590–1630":"1590–1630","1628–1736":"1628–1736","1572–Male":"1572–Surnud","1588":"1588","about 1625":"umbes 1625","1630":"1630","1572":"1572","about 1588":"umbes 1588","1628":"1628","1590":"1590","1736":"1736","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1588–":"noin 1588–Kuollut","1588–Male":"1588–Kuollut","1590–1